{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17607937","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17607937"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T13:27:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T13:27:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15974"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15974"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.13,0.17,0.22,0.43]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8665"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72849"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8665","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8665"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15974"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58319"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8576"},{"type":"tags","id":"10615"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20749"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72849"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring early embryonic development, the blastocyst consists of two distinct cell populations. The outer layer will develop into extraembryonic tissues, while the inner cell mass will form the embryo proper.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures develops into the chorion?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Primitive streak","Inner cell mass","Epiblast","Hypoblast","Trophoblast"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etrophoblast\u003C/strong\u003E is the outer cell layer of the blastocyst that develops into the chorion. The chorion later forms the fetal portion of the placenta and is essential for embryonic nutrition and protection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einner cell mass\u003C/strong\u003E develops into the embryo proper and some extraembryonic membranes, but not the chorion\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypoblast\u003C/strong\u003E forms the yolk sac and contributes to the extraembryonic endoderm\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eepiblast\u003C/strong\u003E gives rise to all three germ layers of the embryo through gastrulation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprimitive streak\u003C/strong\u003E is a structure that forms during gastrulation and establishes the embryonic axis\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe chorion becomes highly vascularised and develops finger-like projections called chorionic villi that increase the surface area for maternal-fetal exchange. The trophoblast differentiates into two layers: the inner cytotrophoblast and outer syncytiotrophoblast.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The trophoblast develops into the chorion, which forms the fetal portion of the placenta.","The chorion is the outermost extraembryonic membrane that surrounds the developing embryo.","The trophoblast differentiates into cytotrophoblast and syncytiotrophoblast layers."],"references":["Menon R, Radnaa E, Behnia F, Urrabaz-Garza R. Isolation and characterization human chorion membrane trophoblast and mesenchymal cells. Placenta. 2020 Nov;101:139-146. doi: 10.1016/j.placenta.2020.09.017. Epub 2020 Sep 19. PMID: 32979718; PMCID: PMC7584780.","Lawless L, Qin Y, Xie L, Zhang K. Trophoblast Differentiation: Mechanisms and Implications for Pregnancy Complications. Nutrients. 2023 Aug 12;15(16):3564. doi: 10.3390/nu15163564. PMID: 37630754; PMCID: PMC10459728.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Padubidri, V. G., \u0026 Daftary, S. N. (Eds.). (2014). Shaw\u0027s Textbook of Gynecology E-book. Elsevier health sciences.","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58319"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15974"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58319"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T10:01:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T10:01:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8665"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72849"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","na